149
00:10:56,586 --> 00:10:57,746
So a couple of ways.

150
00:10:59,267 --> 00:11:02,068
Getting to know people in my own network,

151
00:11:02,928 --> 00:11:08,449
whether that is face-to-face at GDC or PAX or ECGC.

152
00:11:08,910 --> 00:11:11,690
And of course, not everybody can get to conferences.

153
00:11:12,731 --> 00:11:18,032
So in Facebook groups, we have a game writing group.

154
00:11:18,993 --> 00:11:19,533
On Twitter.

155
00:11:20,133 --> 00:11:28,484
And so people have gotten to know me, and when they meet someone who needs a game writer or a narrative designer or even an editor...

156
00:11:29,429 --> 00:11:32,230
They'll give that person my contact information.

157
00:11:33,090 --> 00:11:36,570
I get surprisingly wonderful random emails sometimes,

158
00:11:37,211 --> 00:11:40,071
or I will get someone contacting me

159
00:11:40,131 --> 00:11:43,392
through my website who was referred to me by someone else.

160
00:11:44,052 --> 00:11:45,072
So that's really important.

161
00:11:45,192 --> 00:11:47,353
And then, of course, there's the direct,

162
00:11:48,033 --> 00:11:50,413
you know, I see a posting or something like that,

163
00:11:51,293 --> 00:11:52,914
and I will respond to it.

164
00:11:53,594 --> 00:11:57,595
And I find nowadays, like in the last couple of years,

165
00:11:58,375 --> 00:12:04,317
And it blows my mind, and I guess it shouldn't, but I'm thinking back to the days of when this didn't happen at all.

166
00:12:04,777 --> 00:12:09,819
There are Twitter postings for jobs, you know, and now we're seeing more and more

167
00:12:10,440 --> 00:12:15,122
remote work fine, or you know, freelance contracting remotely fine.

168
00:12:16,802 --> 00:12:21,564
So find those Twitter feeds where people are likely to post jobs,

169
00:12:22,224 --> 00:12:27,607
find groups online over social media or even discussion forums like, you know,

170
00:12:27,747 --> 00:12:32,208
Unity forums or Indie forums where people are posting gigs.

171
00:12:32,408 --> 00:12:35,850
And if they're like Unity or smaller Indies,

172
00:12:36,330 --> 00:12:39,451
they're probably going to be working remotely with people anyway,

173
00:12:39,491 --> 00:12:44,033
because like I said, it's too hard to maintain a physical space.

174
00:12:44,093 --> 00:12:44,933
It's very expensive.

175
00:12:46,198 --> 00:12:50,049
Hashtag game jobs is one of the big ones for Twitter where you

176
00:12:50,069 --> 00:12:50,992
see a lot of postings there.

177
00:12:52,384 --> 00:12:55,747
But yeah, I've noticed that a lot of people,

178
00:12:55,967 --> 00:12:58,490
when they're looking for work, despite the fact

179
00:12:58,510 --> 00:13:00,852
they want to work remotely, they'll still only focus on,

180
00:13:01,332 --> 00:13:02,834
when they're doing the job searches

181
00:13:02,874 --> 00:13:04,695
or looking at studios, they'll focus on ones

182
00:13:04,735 --> 00:13:06,096
that are regionally nearby.

183
00:13:06,437 --> 00:13:10,260
Or they sort of get locked into a tunnel vision of places

184
00:13:10,280 --> 00:13:11,601
they want to live or something like that,

185
00:13:11,982 --> 00:13:13,543
instead of just doing a broad-based search

186
00:13:13,583 --> 00:13:17,687
for every studio or cold calling smaller studios

187
00:13:17,727 --> 00:13:18,387
to see what they need.

188
00:13:20,253 --> 00:13:23,415
So make sure when you're looking for job postings,

189
00:13:23,855 --> 00:13:26,596
it's OK to ping them and ask, hey, can this be remote?

190
00:13:26,816 --> 00:13:29,077
Or, hey, hit them up on Twitter.

191
00:13:29,117 --> 00:13:31,058
Hit their official Twitter account or something like that.

192
00:13:31,078 --> 00:13:32,319
Hey, can this be remote?

193
00:13:32,379 --> 00:13:34,660
I have my qualifications, but I really

