00:13:34,680 --> 00:13:37,301
like the hot dog place down the street,

195
00:13:37,321 --> 00:13:38,741
so I don't really want to move or something like that.

196
00:13:41,873 --> 00:13:44,816
But also, you mentioned coming to GDC.

197
00:13:44,956 --> 00:13:49,421
My first international freelancing work I ever received

198
00:13:49,761 --> 00:13:55,567
was by going to the Swiss Games booth in GDC in 2014

199
00:13:56,107 --> 00:13:58,069
and meeting the designer at BlinFlug.

200
00:13:58,290 --> 00:14:01,232
And we just hit it off and then he mentioned that he needed a game writer

201
00:14:01,513 --> 00:14:03,254
and that's how we developed our relationship.

202
00:14:03,775 --> 00:14:06,538
So walking around and actually introducing yourself,

203
00:14:06,858 --> 00:14:09,601
and not being so upfront to say, you know,

204
00:14:09,621 --> 00:14:11,643
hey, can I work for you, or anything like that,

205
00:14:11,723 --> 00:14:12,984
but just getting to know what their needs are,

206
00:14:13,024 --> 00:14:14,245
getting to know how you can help them out,

207
00:14:14,285 --> 00:14:15,286
getting to know what they're working on,

208
00:14:15,346 --> 00:14:17,208
not necessarily the thing that they're pitching at the moment,

209
00:14:17,248 --> 00:14:17,869
but in the future,

210
00:14:18,509 --> 00:14:19,830
and letting them know that you're available

211
00:14:20,571 --> 00:14:24,095
is an excellent way to start building up that network,

212
00:14:24,115 --> 00:14:25,216
building out your reputation,

213
00:14:26,197 --> 00:14:27,838
and getting your name in front of people's faces.

214
00:14:28,149 --> 00:14:30,710
Let me jump in really quickly about something you said.

215
00:14:30,730 --> 00:14:34,510
A lot of times people don't know that they need you.

216
00:14:35,391 --> 00:14:39,792
You'll hear about a project that they're working on, and they don't have that position filled.

217
00:14:40,732 --> 00:14:44,633
And so when you're talking to someone, whether it's face to face or over email or however,

218
00:14:45,933 --> 00:14:51,794
look very carefully and listen very carefully to the holes that need to be filled, and then

219
00:14:51,874 --> 00:14:53,495
explain how you can fill that hole.

220
00:14:55,563 --> 00:14:58,244
I would say take LinkedIn very seriously.

221
00:14:58,645 --> 00:15:02,406
I know a lot of people just kind of have like a half-assed profile or whatever, but

222
00:15:03,406 --> 00:15:07,868
I noticed that once I started actively updating my LinkedIn

223
00:15:08,148 --> 00:15:11,890
and treating it like a really serious place for people to find me,

224
00:15:12,370 --> 00:15:13,750
people started finding me.

225
00:15:14,951 --> 00:15:20,713
I had three different companies from other countries outside the United States

226
00:15:20,833 --> 00:15:23,314
all contact me based on LinkedIn.

227
00:15:23,854 --> 00:15:28,858
So I think that that's one of the places that people are going to find developers.

228
