they know to ask the questions between 9 and...

449
00:32:15,049 --> 00:32:15,950
one to me.

450
00:32:16,110 --> 00:32:17,832
After that, I'm sleeping.

451
00:32:18,933 --> 00:32:21,656
I am also one of those unstructured night owls.

452
00:32:22,777 --> 00:32:26,420
I go to bed around five or six in the morning, and I

453
00:32:26,480 --> 00:32:28,782
wake up around 1 or 2 in the afternoon.

454
00:32:29,863 --> 00:32:32,926
that's not a given either based on how awake I

455
00:32:33,106 --> 00:32:36,950
am in the early morning or how sleepy I am and I

456
00:32:36,990 --> 00:32:38,511
decide I'm just not going to get up.

457
00:32:39,252 --> 00:32:47,439
But I have found that I tend to divide my day into stuff for other people and stuff for me.

458
00:32:48,459 --> 00:32:51,162
Like Heidi said, everybody's asleep at night.

459
00:32:51,822 --> 00:32:57,607
I tend to work on my own things at night and I'm able to focus better on my own things at night.

460
00:32:58,067 --> 00:33:03,172
I also edit at night because, oddly enough, I find editing very therapeutic.

461
00:33:03,972 --> 00:33:05,914
And so I edit throughout the day.

462
00:33:05,934 --> 00:33:09,858
I tend to do things for clients during the day.

463
00:33:10,859 --> 00:33:13,722
And basically I don't have like an organized schedule.

464
00:33:14,302 --> 00:33:18,166
I figure out with my client when I need to turn things in.

465
00:33:19,107 --> 00:33:24,009
I tend to have two, three weeks before I need to turn something in.

466
00:33:25,209 --> 00:33:29,571
I know how long a particular project is going to take me.

467
00:33:29,611 --> 00:33:34,212
If I have to write a particular document, I know how long it's going to take, so I can

468
00:33:34,672 --> 00:33:37,613
figure out day to day if I want to work on that or not.

469
00:33:38,214 --> 00:33:43,635
So I think if you are used to being in an office and you've had structure before

470
00:33:43,755 --> 00:33:47,295
and you've had a supervisor telling you I need this by X time,

471
00:33:47,956 --> 00:33:53,157
one thing you really need to figure out is how long does it take me to do a certain task?

472
00:33:53,777 --> 00:33:57,578
And so when you are off by your own with no supervision,

473
00:33:58,518 --> 00:34:01,318
you're going to know how you're going to be able to schedule your time.

474
00:34:02,259 --> 00:34:05,720
And Toyo brings up a good point, which is that there are different types of relationships

475
00:34:06,360 --> 00:34:08,961
with your employer when you're doing remote telecommuting.

476
00:34:09,161 --> 00:34:14,544
So if you're on a milestone base where there's a deadline for your work that needs to be turned in,

477
00:34:14,644 --> 00:34:21,326
as opposed to with my work with PlayCorp, it was sort of a daily...

478
00:34:23,617 --> 00:34:26,782
check in and a daily collaborative environment.

479
00:34:27,944 --> 00:34:32,571
And so the type of relationship affects

480
00:34:32,591 --> 00:34:33,452
how you structure your day.

481
00:34:34,554 --> 00:34:37,538
So that if you don't, it sounds like if you.

482
00:34:39,180 --> 00:34:41,401
if you don't need to be available to them at all times,

483
00:34:41,762 --> 00:34:43,342
then you can have a little more flexibility

484
00:34:43,382 --> 00:34:45,903
with your own personal time or the way you structure your day.

485
00:34:45,924 --> 00:34:48,445
Whereas if you are somebody who is telecommuting

486
00:34:49,285 --> 00:34:51,926
and your time zones basically align

487
00:34:52,527 --> 00:34:54,568
the same as the client or the employer,

488
00:34:55,308 --> 00:34:56,729
you might be expected to be on Slack

489
00:34:57,029 --> 00:35:01,011
or any other proprietary chat services all the time

490
00:35:01,031 --> 00:35:02,211
so you can answer questions like that.

491
00:35:02,251 --> 00:35:05,353
So again, it's about negotiating with your employer,

492
00:35:05,413 --> 00:35:06,873
negotiating with your client to figure out.

493
00:35:07,825 --> 00:35:11,206
What works best, but knowing what works best for you at the same time.

494
00:35:11,646 --> 00:35:14,627
Yeah, I went from working 9-5 office,

495
00:35:15,228 --> 00:35:19,909
and then going to the games industry, which was studio culture, which was totally different.

496
00:35:20,450 --> 00:35:23,871
And then I went from studio culture to working remotely.

497
00:35:23,931 --> 00:35:26,312
So I've done all three things at this point.

498
00:35:27,132 --> 00:35:31,814
And the one thing that I found the hardest when switching over to remote work

499
00:35:31,914 --> 00:35:33,934
was getting used to asking questions.

500
00:35:34,735 --> 00:35:41,197
It's like I am not somebody who will inherently always ask a whole lot of questions about what I'm supposed to be doing,

501
00:35:41,637 --> 00:35:46,879
but it is necessary to do when you're working remotely, even if you think it's obvious, it might not be.

502
00:35:47,480 --> 00:35:50,001
And so I'll proceed my question with something like,

503
00:35:50,021 --> 00:35:52,902
this is probably a stupid question, but I just want to be clear.

504
00:35:53,262 --> 00:35:59,764
And it's like asking tons of those little questions to make sure that you understand what it is that they want you to do,

505
00:36:00,965 --> 00:36:03,326
or that they understood what you were telling them.

506
00:36:03,806 --> 00:36:07,408
And that becomes especially true if there's a language barrier.

507
00:36:09,870 --> 00:36:14,453
But yes, you will become friendly with asking questions.

508
00:36:15,941 --> 00:36:21,946
And of course something to realize on that level is, because I'm sort of, I've had the opposite problem.

509
00:36:21,966 --> 00:36:28,971
I'm always asking questions and then realizing, oh wait, my clients are at, you know, are in bed at prime

510
00:36:28,991 --> 00:36:38,898
I need to ask this question time. How do I manage that? And so it has been like, ideally, yes, you get this all laid out at the very beginning.

511
00:36:39,399 --> 00:36:42,922
But don't blame yourself if it's also a work in progress,

512
00:36:42,962 --> 00:36:45,705
that if you start it and you figure after a while,

513
00:36:45,745 --> 00:36:49,148
like, no, I actually do need more direct feedback.

514
00:36:49,188 --> 00:36:50,530
I need to be able to ask questions

515
00:36:50,570 --> 00:36:51,811
and get them answered right away.

516
00:36:51,831 --> 00:36:53,252
Talk to your client about.

517
00:36:55,675 --> 00:37:00,680
you know, how to get that working, you know, think about how you can maybe rearrange your schedule.

518
00:37:01,621 --> 00:37:05,465
Something else to consider that I think a lot of people maybe don't consider, and that is

519
00:37:06,306 --> 00:37:10,210
it's not only just about your structure, it's about the structure of your client.

520
00:37:11,251 --> 00:37:18,218
We tend to assume that the clients we have are all, you know, 9 to 5, like, office hours in whatever their time zone is.

521
00:37:18,939 --> 00:37:24,685
You may be working with an indie who's like working out of their bedroom or their basement

522
00:37:25,185 --> 00:37:29,270
and they will be keeping very, very unusual hours as well.

523
00:37:29,730 --> 00:37:33,914
So my current situation is I have two clients, one that's in China

524
00:37:34,155 --> 00:37:36,918
and that has involved me shifting my schedule around.

525
00:37:37,318 --> 00:37:43,940
to match, you know, they're a full office, they're, you know, nine, like, ten to seven Beijing time,

526
00:37:44,321 --> 00:37:45,981
and so I have to adjust to that.

527
00:37:46,301 --> 00:37:50,503
But then my other client is an Indie in Hungary, and he stays up till two in the morning.

528
00:37:51,743 --> 00:37:56,125
So he, like, it's actually really easy to get hold of him during my workday.

529
00:37:56,465 --> 00:38:02,468
So that's something to consider when you're looking at clients, that the type of client you work with

530
00:38:03,710 --> 00:38:05,755
may affect the sort of schedule they have.

531
00:38:05,815 --> 00:38:09,544
So don't jump to assumptions of everything has to be on their 9-5.

532
00:38:09,704 --> 00:38:11,248
It could be on your 9-5.

533
00:38:13,377 --> 00:38:18,538
And I'll jump in and say that I work best from 9 p.m. to 5 a.m.

534
00:38:18,638 --> 00:38:24,199
So in there with a couple folks up here and that is actually that's part of the criteria

535
00:38:24,239 --> 00:38:28,060
I think about when I am seeking out clients, folks who are at least like eight hours

536
00:38:29,201 --> 00:38:32,682
ahead of me, so that can help you narrow down if again wondering where to start.

537
00:38:34,382 --> 00:38:36,423
Also as far as how do I get to work?

538
00:38:37,824 --> 00:38:42,728
I personally find it helpful to do kind of a centering activity that's relevant to me.

539
00:38:42,768 --> 00:38:48,153
That could be a spiritual, religious thing, or something as simple as doing power poses even.

540
00:38:48,753 --> 00:38:51,476
So again, if you're just kind of looking for something to jump start, you know,

541
00:38:51,496 --> 00:38:54,459
when you're in your home, but know you need to do work.

542
00:38:55,580 --> 00:39:01,464
And a separate that I'll just add to that too is increasingly there are shared workspaces available out there

543
00:39:02,145 --> 00:39:03,866
for telecommuters and freelancers.

544
00:39:05,367 --> 00:39:09,611
I'm pretty sure San Francisco has a bunch of them. I feel like I've seen a few, Seattle, Austin,

545
00:39:10,291 --> 00:39:16,797
and that's the sort of thing where you can rent out like a little cubicle typically for a certain amount of time or

546
00:39:16,877 --> 00:39:18,358
potentially for weeks at a time.

547
00:39:19,118 --> 00:39:24,461
I was just going to add to that, changing your setting once a week may also help.

548
00:39:24,661 --> 00:39:25,441
I do that as well.

549
00:39:26,762 --> 00:39:33,424
One day a week, around 2pm, I go to my favorite little pizza spot where I can go to the booth

550
00:39:33,464 --> 00:39:33,965
in the back.

551
00:39:34,725 --> 00:39:35,325
And I know...

552
00:39:36,094 --> 00:39:41,619
I am getting work done today, and I sit there from around 2 p.m. to 10 p.m.

553
00:39:42,560 --> 00:39:46,724
And so I know I'm going to be focused today, I am leaving my house,

554
00:39:47,305 --> 00:39:50,068
I am not going to have the distractions that I usually have.

555
00:39:51,222 --> 00:39:54,823
I do a similar thing with, you know, the stereotypical cafe.

556
00:39:54,863 --> 00:39:56,964
I'll sit in a cafe in the corner and do my work.

557
00:39:58,765 --> 00:40:01,867
I always recommend people who do stuff like that to maintain a really good relationship

558
00:40:01,907 --> 00:40:06,709
with the staff there because they get to know you and you don't want to be that jerk that

559
00:40:06,749 --> 00:40:10,170
is always coming in and not tipping and just sitting at the table and, you know, taking

560
00:40:10,190 --> 00:40:10,551
up space.

561
00:40:11,171 --> 00:40:13,572
If you have a spot, be kind to those people.

562
00:40:14,532 --> 00:40:15,413
You want them to like you.

563
00:40:17,573 --> 00:40:25,295
Something else to consider, you know, obviously we've been talking about how to deal with distractions and how to resist distractions, and that is very important,

564
00:40:25,935 --> 00:40:35,698
but I also think that, you know, to a certain extent, we tend to think of distraction as like, you know, a pure enemy, that there is nothing good about distraction,

565
00:40:35,738 --> 00:40:45,220
but sometimes a short and managed distraction is kind of what you need to sort of reset your mind space and get, like, that burst of energy.

566
00:40:46,160 --> 00:40:50,202
That's why I've been actually experimenting recently with the Pomodoro technique,

567
00:40:50,222 --> 00:40:53,864
which is very much kind of like you set a timer, you work for 25 minutes,

568
00:40:53,924 --> 00:40:58,307
and then you have five minutes of free time that you can do something else.

569
00:40:58,387 --> 00:41:01,909
And I find that that actually helps when it's, you know, after the five minutes,

570
00:41:01,949 --> 00:41:06,111
I'm like, okay, even though I wasn't directly thinking about what I had to write,

571
00:41:06,551 --> 00:41:08,872
it's helped reset my mind space a bit.

572
00:41:08,933 --> 00:41:12,595
Now obviously, some of you may find that you need to get into a flow state,

573
00:41:12,615 --> 00:41:13,635
you need to not stop.

574
00:41:14,135 --> 00:41:16,697
But I suppose my recommendation would be,

575
00:41:17,678 --> 00:41:21,021
if you find that there are types of short, short,

576
00:41:21,401 --> 00:41:26,085
distractions in your day that can help you get back to work,

577
00:41:26,145 --> 00:41:27,566
help you keep your energy up,

578
00:41:27,987 --> 00:41:31,069
then don't beat yourself up for,

579
00:41:31,570 --> 00:41:32,911
quote unquote, succumbing to them.

580
00:41:33,391 --> 00:41:36,854
As long as you get your work done by the deadline,

581
00:41:37,755 --> 00:41:38,676
do what you have to do.

582
00:41:40,055 --> 00:41:49,702
And if it is physically possible for you, and you're not in a flow state, get up and walk around like every 25, 20-25 minutes.

583
00:41:50,342 --> 00:41:54,385
Because sitting in front of a laptop, even if you can't sense it, is incredibly draining.

584
00:41:54,905 --> 00:42:00,549
And also just because you're working, you're putting a lot of physical and emotional and mental effort into what you're doing.

585
00:42:01,090 --> 00:42:05,553
And so, you know, getting up or moving around recharges your batteries. It's really important.

586
00:42:06,766 --> 00:42:07,969
All right, thanks so much.

587
00:42:08,570 --> 00:42:11,959
Our next question is, what are some technological hurdles

588
00:42:12,039 --> 00:42:14,165
to telecommuting, and what are your suggestions

589
00:42:14,205 --> 00:42:15,007
for resolving them?

590
00:42:18,711 --> 00:42:22,052
Just have the help desk information.

591
00:42:22,092 --> 00:42:24,473
Like if it's a help desk you're supposed to talk to,

592
00:42:24,493 --> 00:42:26,874
if it's a person you're supposed to talk to,

593
00:42:27,314 --> 00:42:29,135
have that information at the ready.

594
00:42:30,516 --> 00:42:33,197
I've run into a situation where one of the tools

595
00:42:33,457 --> 00:42:34,957
that I'm supposed to be working with

596
00:42:35,357 --> 00:42:38,799
is for whatever reason not working correctly on my laptop.

597
00:42:39,339 --> 00:42:42,060
And so that means that until we get that situated,

598
00:42:42,080 --> 00:42:45,141
I have to compose the game dialogue

599
00:42:45,181 --> 00:42:46,882
directly into the code of the game.

600
00:42:48,866 --> 00:42:52,900
And, you know, anyone who knows me knows that you probably don't want me in your code.

601
00:42:54,781 --> 00:43:03,606
Luckily, they gave me a longer deadline because they knew that it was like really hard to like try to parse out visually where I'm supposed to put things.

602
00:43:03,666 --> 00:43:09,210
But that's just the kind of thing that can happen and you just kind of roll with it.

603
00:43:09,330 --> 00:43:18,235
And I know when I get back from GDC, we're going to be doing a step-by-step, you know, figure out how to make the tool work on my computer thing.

604
00:43:18,775 --> 00:43:20,856
And if not, we've got the hacky way.

605
00:43:23,507 --> 00:43:26,830
This actually kind of dovetails nicely with what we were just talking about in terms of

606
00:43:28,572 --> 00:43:34,077
these types of challenges, technological hurdles, are best overcome by communicating

607
00:43:34,497 --> 00:43:39,122
with your client or the employer as quickly as possible, as clearly as possible,

608
00:43:39,202 --> 00:43:42,605
giving them specific details about the problem that you're having or the question that you have.

609
00:43:43,386 --> 00:43:49,928
And if you've established a communication pipeline that's been working, it should be pretty straightforward to resolve these problems.

610
00:43:50,308 --> 00:43:54,269
But it's about, up front, knowing that you need to establish a communication pipeline.

611
00:43:54,490 --> 00:43:58,991
Who you need to talk to, who's in charge of making this decision or resolving the problem.

612
00:44:00,232 --> 00:44:03,633
And not having it be, oh, you gotta go talk to Joe, he's the so-and-so person.

613
00:44:03,913 --> 00:44:05,133
Oh, no, actually you need to talk to...

614
00:44:05,673 --> 00:44:08,274
Jane, she's the person that handles questions from people.

615
00:44:08,294 --> 00:44:11,556
Keeping your supervisor in the loop as well all the time.

616
00:44:11,576 --> 00:44:16,860
So like having a point of contact, a specific point of contact, if possible, with a department

617
00:44:17,220 --> 00:44:22,963
is really important so that you always have a, yeah, you know exactly who you need to

618
00:44:23,003 --> 00:44:23,263
go to.

619
00:44:24,149 --> 00:44:31,770
A couple of points. The communication pipeline is very important, something that I have a really difficult time with.

620
00:44:32,610 --> 00:44:44,053
I'm working with devs who like to make major decisions in Skype chats, and there can be 50 posts, 50 messages in Skype.

621
00:44:45,093 --> 00:44:49,234
And there have been times where a major change was implemented.

622
00:44:50,094 --> 00:44:57,641
And a couple of us didn't know, because it happened in Skype like two days ago, 50 messages away.

623
00:44:58,402 --> 00:45:03,726
And it was like three weeks later when we found out there was a major implementation change.

624
00:45:04,467 --> 00:45:06,469
And so there needs to be one place.

625
00:45:09,912 --> 00:45:12,313
where all of the documentation is,

626
00:45:12,333 --> 00:45:15,794
and everybody needs to decide where that place is,

627
00:45:15,814 --> 00:45:17,075
and to make sure,

628
00:45:17,095 --> 00:45:19,916
hey, have there been changes made?

629
00:45:20,356 --> 00:45:23,557
Please keep those changes in the documentation

630
00:45:24,258 --> 00:45:27,039
so that I'm working with the most recent information.

631
00:45:28,039 --> 00:45:31,020
And that's just important, not just for you, so you're not frustrated,

632
00:45:31,721 --> 00:45:35,022
but if people don't have that information, that can set the project back.

633
00:45:35,942 --> 00:45:40,446
The other thing is, if you are in a subcontracting position,

634
00:45:40,626 --> 00:45:43,688
in other words, there is a contractor that's working with a client,

635
00:45:44,188 --> 00:45:48,091
and then they find you and you are actually working for the contractor,

636
00:45:48,691 --> 00:45:54,235
make sure you are also in communication with the person who is going to be approving your work.

637
00:45:54,936 --> 00:45:57,318
Because that's going to be the contractor's client.

638
00:45:57,878 --> 00:46:01,741
I was in a position where I had no communication with the client.

639
00:46:02,461 --> 00:46:05,123
And I was trying to do my work.

640
00:46:05,844 --> 00:46:07,665
I was asking lots of questions.

641
00:46:08,326 --> 00:46:12,869
The contractor was trying to do his best to get the answer to those questions, and he couldn't.

642
00:46:13,790 --> 00:46:18,933
And that was probably very, very early in my career where I did not know to say,

643
00:46:18,954 --> 00:46:24,658
hey, I also need the email address or the phone number of the client so I can contact them directly.

644
00:46:28,443 --> 00:46:33,265
I'll actually say one of the technical issues that I've had has been, of course,

645
00:46:33,305 --> 00:46:37,026
like one of the things that, you know, is supposed to help, particularly for writers,

646
00:46:37,306 --> 00:46:44,508
is prototyping and, you know, putting the text into, say, Unity and, you know, seeing how it plays out.

647
00:46:45,649 --> 00:46:55,974
I have not had the greatest luck at having, at trying to organize with clients to set up my system so that I can actually do that myself.

648
00:46:56,054 --> 00:47:02,318
So what, you know, tends to happen is I, you know, send off my text to China and they do the prototyping on their end.

649
00:47:02,958 --> 00:47:06,979
I get a video of it, but I don't get to actually do it myself.

650
00:47:07,279 --> 00:47:08,920
And I've asked them multiple times,

651
00:47:08,960 --> 00:47:11,420
hey, could we put Unity on my, you know,

652
00:47:11,460 --> 00:47:13,921
could we get Unity set up so that I can do this too?

653
00:47:14,001 --> 00:47:16,762
And they're like, we have other things to do.

654
00:47:17,382 --> 00:47:18,682
We can't really do that right now.

655
00:47:19,783 --> 00:47:21,503
So depending on your discipline, you

656
00:47:21,583 --> 00:47:26,305
may end up being a little siloed off from things that way.

657
00:47:27,546 --> 00:47:33,491
At which point you just sort of have to communicate with the client and work with what you can do.

658
00:47:33,551 --> 00:47:41,979
So like, hence, you know, I said, okay, well, if you, you know, if I can't actually see what these scenes look like myself, can someone make videos for me?

659
00:47:42,059 --> 00:47:43,200
Oh yeah, sure, we can do that.

660
00:47:44,881 --> 00:47:49,605
So it's something to consider that maybe early on the process, if you get the chance,

661
00:47:51,186 --> 00:47:57,792
make sure that you're onboarded with the tools that you can actually prototype and see the game

662
00:47:57,832 --> 00:47:59,873
and see the scenes and see the things that you're doing,

663
00:48:00,534 --> 00:48:05,378
because otherwise you basically have to send it off into the ether,

664
00:48:05,538 --> 00:48:07,159
and then eventually someone comes back and says,

665
00:48:07,440 --> 00:48:09,862
we put it all on Unity and it sucks, go do it again.

666
